# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: christopher-c-kraft-jr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] An **acolyte** is an assistant or follower assisting the celebrant in a religious service or procession.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In many Christian denominations, an acolyte is anyone performing ceremonial duties such as lighting altar candles.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In others, the term is used for one who has been inducted into a particular liturgical ministry, even when not performing those duties.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The word *acolyte* is derived from the Greek word ἀκόλουθος (*akolouthos*), meaning an attendant, via Late Latin *acolythus*.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In the Eastern Orthodox, Eastern Lutheran and Byzantine Rite Eastern Catholic Churches, the nearest equivalent of acolyte is the altar server.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] At one time there was a rank of minor clergy called the *taper-bearer* (κηροφόρος) responsible for bearing lights during processions and liturgical entrances.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] However, this rank has long ago been subsumed by that of the reader and the service for the tonsure of a reader begins with the setting-aside of a taper-bearer.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The functions of an acolyte or taper-bearer are therefore carried out by readers, subdeacons, or by non-tonsured men or boys who are sometimes called "acolytes" informally.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Also, the term "altar-boys" is often used to refer to young altar servers.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Subdeacons wear their normal vestments consisting of the sticharion and crossed orarion; readers and servers traditionally wear the sticharion alone.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In recent times, however, in many of the North American Greek Orthodox Churches, for the sake of uniformity, readers have been permitted to wear the orarion (the bishop presents the reader, who is to serve on the altar, with the orarion).
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Readers do not cross the orarion while wearing it, the uncrossed orarion being intended to slightly distinguish a reader from a subdeacon.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In some churches wear both the sticharion and orarion, while others use the orarion alone.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In other churches, acolytes are asked to be neatly dressed, and to fast completely each Sunday until Holy Communion is completed.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In the Russian tradition, readers wear only the sticharion, and do not wear the orarion unless they have been specially blessed to by their bishop.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] (This might be done if a reader must occasionally serve in the role of a subdeacon, or for some other reason the bishop believes is fitting.) If a server has not been tonsured, he must remove the sticharion before he can receive Holy Communion.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Until 1972, the highest of the four minor orders in the Latin Church was that of acolyte.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] By his *motu proprio* *Ministeria quaedam* of 15 August 1972, Pope Paul VI replaced the term "minor orders" by that of "ministries" and the term "ordination" by "institution".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] He kept throughout the Latin Church two now-titled instituted ministries, those of reader and acolyte.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] A prescribed interval, as decided by the Holy See and the national episcopal conference, is to be observed between receiving the two.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Candidates for diaconate and for priesthood must receive both ministries and exercise them for some time before receiving holy orders.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The two instituted ministries are not reserved solely for candidates for holy orders.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Ministries are conferred by the ordinary: either a bishop or the head of a similar territory or, in the case of clerical religious institutes, a major superior.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Institutions of acolytes not preparing for holy orders are in fact sometimes carried out.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The *motu proprio* assigned to the instituted acolyte the functions previously reserved for the subdeacon, and declared national episcopal conferences free to use the term "subdeacon" in place of that of "acolyte".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The functions of the instituted acolyte are specified in the *motu proprio*, and have been indicated also in the General Instruction of the Roman Missal, no.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] 98, which under the heading, "The Ministry of the Instituted Acolyte and Lector", says: "The acolyte is instituted to serve at the altar and to assist the priest and deacon.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In particular, it is his responsibility to prepare the altar and the sacred vessels and, if it is necessary, as an extraordinary minister, to distribute the Eucharist to the faithful.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In the ministry of the altar, the acolyte has his own functions (cf. nos.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] As in other churches, in the Latin Church the term "acolyte" is also used of altar servers on whom no ordination or institution has been conferred.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Pope Benedict XVI spoke of Saint Tarcisius as "presumably an acolyte, that is, an altar server".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Pope Francis changed canon law in January 2021 to allow female installed acolytes.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Before his *motu proprio Spiritus Domini*, only men could be installed acolytes.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] While the approved English translations of the liturgical books of the Catholic Church's Roman Rite use the term "instituted" (such as "instituted acolytes" and "instituted lectors") some translations refer to them as "installed".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] For example, the translation on the Vatican's website of the 2019 Motu Proprio Aperuit illis – Instituting the Sunday of the Word of God has "Bishops could celebrate the Rite of Installation of Lectors or a similar commissioning of readers …".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In the Lutheran Churches, acolytes have various responsibilities, such as ringing the church bells and lighting the candles in the chancel.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Certain acolytes are assigned the role of crucifer or thurifer, who carry the processional cross and thurible respectively.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The torchbearer stands to the side of the crucifer to carry candles, during the procession and recession.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The bannerbearer typically carries a gonfalon in processions and recessions.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Acolytes typically wear albs and the cincture used may reflect the colour of the liturgical season in the Christian calendar.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The role of the acolyte is considered important in Lutheranism as those who serve in these roles, typically youth, often develop an interest in holy orders.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The order of acolyte was not initially retained with Anglicanism during the English Reformation therefore there is no definition of their role in the Book of Common Prayer 1662.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] The use of acolytes (like many Anglican practices) is very much dependent on local practice, some parishes may refer to altar servers as *acolytes,* whereas other parishes may have them as a distinctive and formal ministry.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Then in Low or Evangelical Parishes the use of Acolytes or altar servers may not exist at all.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Where acolytes are used, opinions on gender and age vary.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In the Methodist tradition, acolytes may participate in the worship service by carrying a processional cross or crucifix (these acolytes are called crucifers), lighting and extinguishing the altar candles, and ringing the church bell to call the congregation to worship.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] In these traditions, the lighting of the altar candles in the worship service is a symbol of Jesus' coming into the presence of the worshiping community.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Before lighting the candles the acolyte may bow at the altar out of respect.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Before the extinguishing of the last altar candles, the acolytes relight their "candle lighter" and then process out into the narthex.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] This symbolizes that Jesus Christ is for all people everywhere.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] It also symbolizes the light of Jesus Christ going out into the world where believers are called to serve.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/acolyte] Acolytes in these traditions wear robes called albs, sometimes with a cincture; alternatively Methodist acolytes in other congregations wear the traditional cassock and cotta.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The **administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration** is the highest-ranking official of NASA, the national space agency of the United States.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The administrator is NASA's chief decision maker, responsible for providing clarity to the agency's vision and serving as a source of internal leadership within NASA.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The office holder also has an important place within United States space policy, and is assisted by a deputy administrator.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The administrator is appointed by the president of the United States, with the advice and consent of the United States Senate, and thereafter serves at the president's pleasure.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Jared Isaacman has served as the administrator since December 18, 2025.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The administrator serves as NASA's chief executive officer, accountable to the president for the leadership necessary to achieve the agency's mission.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] This leadership requires articulating the agency's vision, setting its programmatic and budget priorities and internal policies, and assessing agency performance.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Keith Glennan; during his term he brought together the disparate projects in space development research in the US.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Within a short time after NASA's formal organization, Glennan incorporated several organizations involved in space exploration projects from other federal agencies into NASA.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] He brought in part of the Naval Research Laboratory and created the Goddard Space Flight Center.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] He also incorporated several disparate satellite programs, two lunar probes, and the research effort to develop a million pound force (4.4 MN) thrust, single-chamber rocket engine from the U.S.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Department of Defense's (DOD) Advanced Research Projects Agency.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] In December 1958 Glennan also acquired control of the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, a contractor facility operated by the California Institute of Technology.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] In 1960, Glennan obtained the transfer to NASA of the Army Ballistic Missile Agency, located at Huntsville, Alabama, and renamed it the Marshall Space Flight Center.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Webb, served from 1961 to 1968, from the beginning of the Kennedy administration through the end of the Johnson administration, thus overseeing each of the critical first crewed missions throughout the Mercury and Gemini programs until days before the launch of the first Apollo mission.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] During Webb's administration, NASA developed from a loose collection of research centers to a coordinated organization.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] He had a key role in creating the Manned Spacecraft Center, later the Johnson Space Center, in Houston.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Despite the pressures to focus on the Apollo program, Webb ensured that NASA carried out a program of planetary exploration with the Mariner and Pioneer space programs.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Webb was an early champion of space telescopes, like the one that would later bear his name.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Encouraged by Kennedy and Johnson, Webb made racial integration a priority for the agency.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] NASA publicly supported the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and initiated a series of innovative programs aimed at increasing black participation including specifically targeting black colleges and schools with recruitment programs.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The only person to hold the post twice is James C.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] During his first administration at NASA, Fletcher was responsible for beginning the Space Shuttle effort, as well as the Viking program that sent landers to Mars.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] He oversaw the Skylab missions and approved the Voyager space probes and the Apollo–Soyuz Test Project.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] He returned to NASA following the *Challenger* disaster.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Daniel Goldin held the post for the longest term (nearly 10 years), and is best known for pioneering the "faster, better, cheaper" approach to space programs.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] The current administrator is entrepreneur and philanthropist Jared Isaacman, who was nominated by President Donald Trump on November 5, 2025.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] He replaced Sean Duffy, who served as acting administrator from July 9, 2025 to December 17, 2025.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/administrator-of-nasa] Jared Isaacman was nominated by Trump (while he was president-elect) on December 4, 2024, but his nomination was withdrawn on May 31, reportedly because of his connections to Elon Musk and donations towards Democratic, anti-Trump politicians.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] "Aeronautical engineering" was the original term for the field.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] As flight technology advanced to include vehicles operating in outer space, the broader term "aerospace engineering" has come into use.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Aerospace engineering, particularly the astronautics branch, is often colloquially referred to as "rocket science".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Flight vehicles are subjected to demanding conditions such as those caused by changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature, with structural loads applied upon vehicle components.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Consequently, they are usually the products of various technological and engineering disciplines including aerodynamics, air propulsion, avionics, materials science, structural analysis and manufacturing.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The interaction between these technologies is known as aerospace engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Because of the complexity and number of disciplines involved, aerospace engineering is carried out by teams of engineers, each having their own specialized area of expertise.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The origin of aerospace engineering can be traced back to the aviation pioneers around the late 19th to early 20th centuries, although the work of Sir George Cayley dates from the last decade of the 18th to the mid-19th century.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] One of the most important people in the history of aeronautics and a pioneer in aeronautical engineering, Cayley is credited as the first person to separate the forces of lift and drag, which affect any atmospheric flight vehicle.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Early knowledge of aeronautical engineering was largely empirical, with some concepts and skills imported from other branches of engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Some key elements, like fluid dynamics, were understood by 18th-century scientists.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] In December 1903, the Wright Brothers performed the first sustained, controlled flight of a powered, heavier-than-air aircraft, lasting 12 seconds.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The 1910s saw the development of aeronautical engineering through the design of World War I military aircraft.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] In 1914, Robert Goddard was granted two U.S. patents for rockets using solid fuel, liquid fuel, multiple propellant charges, and multi-stage designs.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] This would set the stage for future applications in multi-stage propulsion systems for outer space.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Congress established the first aeronautical research administration, known as the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, or NACA.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] It was the first government-sponsored organization to support aviation research.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Though intended as an advisory board upon inception, the Langley Aeronautical Laboratory became its first sponsored research and testing facility in 1920.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The organization would later be redefined as NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Between World Wars I and II, great leaps were made in the field, accelerated by the advent of mainstream civil aviation.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Notable airplanes of this era include the Curtiss JN 4, Farman F.60 Goliath, and Fokker Trimotor.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Notable military airplanes of this period include the Mitsubishi A6M Zero, Supermarine Spitfire and Messerschmitt Bf 109 from Japan, United Kingdom, and Germany respectively.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] A significant development came with the first operational Jet engine-powered airplane, the Messerschmitt Me 262 which entered service in 1944 towards the end of the Second World War.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The first definition of aerospace engineering appeared in February 1958, considering the Earth's atmosphere and outer space as a single realm, thereby encompassing both aircraft (*aero*) and spacecraft (*space*) under the newly coined term *aerospace*.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] In response to the USSR launching the first satellite, Sputnik, into space on October 4, 1957, U.S. aerospace engineers launched the first American satellite on January 31, 1958.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was founded in 1958 after the Sputnik crisis.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] In 1969, Apollo 11, the first human space mission to land on the Moon, took place.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] It saw three astronauts enter orbit around the Moon, with two, Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin, visiting the lunar surface.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The third astronaut, Michael Collins, stayed in orbit to rendezvous with Armstrong and Aldrin after their visit.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] An important innovation came on January 30, 1970, when the Boeing 747 made its first commercial flight from New York to London.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] This aircraft made history and became known as the "Jumbo Jet" or "Queen of the Skies" due to its ability to hold up to 480 passengers.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Another significant development came in 1976, with the development of the first passenger supersonic aircraft, the Concorde.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The development of this aircraft was agreed upon by the French and British on November 29, 1962.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] On December 21, 1988, the Antonov An-225 *Mriya* cargo aircraft commenced its first flight.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] It holds the records for the world's heaviest aircraft, heaviest airlifted cargo, and longest airlifted cargo of any aircraft in operational service.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] On October 25, 2007, the Airbus A380 made its maiden commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney, Australia.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] This aircraft was the first passenger plane to surpass the Boeing 747 in terms of passenger capacity, with a maximum of 853.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Though development of this aircraft began in 1988 as a competitor to the 747, the A380 made its first test flight in April 2005.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The basis of most of these elements lies in theoretical physics, such as fluid dynamics for aerodynamics or the equations of motion for flight dynamics.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] There is also a large empirical component.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Historically, this empirical component was derived from testing of scale models and prototypes, either in wind tunnels or in the free atmosphere.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] More recently, advances in computing have enabled the use of computational fluid dynamics to simulate the behavior of the fluid, reducing time and expense spent on wind-tunnel testing.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Those studying hydrodynamics or hydroacoustics often obtain degrees in aerospace engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Aerospace engineering may be studied at the advanced diploma, bachelor's, master's, and Ph.D. levels in aerospace engineering departments at many universities, and in mechanical engineering departments at others.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] A few departments offer degrees in space-focused astronautical engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Some institutions differentiate between aeronautical and astronautical engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Graduate degrees are offered in advanced or specialty areas for the aerospace industry.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] A background in chemistry, physics, computer science and mathematics is important for students pursuing an aerospace engineering degree.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The term "rocket scientist" is sometimes used to describe a person of great intelligence since rocket science is seen as a practice requiring great mental ability, especially technically and mathematically.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The term is used ironically in the expression "It's not rocket science" to indicate that a task is simple.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] Strictly speaking, the use of "science" in "rocket science" is a misnomer since science is about understanding the origins, nature, and behavior of the universe; engineering is about using scientific and engineering principles to solve problems and develop new technology.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] The more etymologically correct version of this phrase would be "rocket engineer".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/aeronautical-engineering] However, "science" and "engineering" are often misused as synonyms.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He worked for over a decade in aeronautical research and in 1958 joined the Space Task Group, a small team entrusted with the responsibility of putting America's first man in space.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Assigned to the flight operations division, Kraft became NASA's first flight director.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He was on duty during America's first crewed spaceflight, first crewed orbital flight, and first spacewalk.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] At the beginning of the Apollo program, Kraft retired as a flight director to concentrate on management and mission planning.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1972, he became director of the Manned Spacecraft Center (later Johnson Space Center), following his mentor Robert R.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Gilruth, and held the position until his retirement in 1982.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Later, Kraft consulted for companies such as IBM and Rockwell International.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1994, he was appointed chairman of a panel to make NASA's Space Shuttle program more cost effective.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The panel's controversial report, known as the *Kraft report*, recommended that NASA's Space Shuttle operations should be outsourced to a private contractor.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] It also recommended that NASA cut back on the organizational changes intended to improve safety that were made after the Space Shuttle *Challenger* disaster.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] This attracted even more critical comment after the Space Shuttle *Columbia* disaster.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft published his autobiography *Flight: My Life in Mission Control* in 2001.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The Mission Control Center building was named after him in 2011.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] When he received the National Space Trophy from the Rotary Club in 1999, the organization described him as "a driving force in the U.S. human space flight program from its beginnings to the Space Shuttle era, a man whose accomplishments have become legendary".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Christopher Columbus Kraft Jr. was born in Phoebus, Virginia, on February 28, 1924.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He was named after his father, Christopher Columbus Kraft, who was born in New York City in 1892 near the newly renamed Columbus Circle.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft's father, the son of Bavarian immigrants, had found his name an embarrassment, but passed it along to his son nonetheless.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In later years, Kraft—as well as other commentators—would consider it peculiarly appropriate.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft commented in his autobiography that, with the choice of his name, "some of my life's direction was settled from the start".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] His mother, Vanda Olivia (née Suddreth), was a nurse.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] As a boy, Kraft played in an American Legion drum-and-bugle corps and became the state champion bugler.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He went to school in Phoebus, where the only school went to the ninth grade and attended Hampton High School.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He was a keen baseball player and continued to play the sport in college; one year he had a batting average of .340.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In September 1941, Kraft began his studies at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University (Virginia Tech) and became a Cadet in the Corps of Cadets as a member of N-Squadron.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The United States entered World War II in December 1941, and he attempted to enlist in the United States Navy as a V-12 aviation cadet, but was rejected because of a burned right hand that he had suffered at age three.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He graduated in December 1944 with a Bachelor of Science degree in aeronautical engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On graduation, Kraft accepted a job with the Chance Vought aircraft company in Connecticut.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He had also applied to the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA), a government agency whose Langley Research Center was in Hampton, Virginia; Kraft considered it to be too close to home, but applied as a back-up if he was not accepted elsewhere.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On arrival to begin work at Chance Vought in Bridgeport, Connecticut he was told during three successive attempts that he could not enter the plant without his birth certificate, which he had not brought with him and which he then attempted to procure.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Annoyed by the repeated obstructive mindset of the clerk at the front gate, he decided to accept the offer from NACA instead.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In the 1940s, NACA was a research and development organization, devoted to cutting-edge aeronautical research.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] At the Langley Research Center, advanced wind tunnels were used to test new aircraft designs, and studies were taking place on new concepts such as the Bell X-1 rocket plane.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was assigned to the flight research division, where Robert R.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] His work with NACA included the development of an early example of gust alleviation systems for aircraft flying in turbulent air.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] This involved compensating for variations in the atmosphere by automatically deflecting the control surfaces.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He investigated wingtip vortices, and discovered that they, and not prop-wash, are responsible for most of the wake turbulence in the air that trails flying aircraft.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Although he enjoyed his work, Kraft found it increasingly stressful, especially since he did not consider himself to be a strong theoretician.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1956, he was diagnosed with an ulcer and started thinking about a change of career.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1957, the Soviet flight of Sputnik 1 prompted the United States to accelerate its fledgling space program.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Eisenhower signed the National Aeronautics and Space Act, which established NASA and subsumed NACA within this newly created organization.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Langley Research Center became a part of NASA, as did Langley employees such as Kraft.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Even before NASA began its official existence in October, Kraft was invited by Gilruth to become a part of a new group that was working on the problems of putting a man into orbit.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Without much hesitation, he accepted the offer.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] When the Space Task Group was officially formed on November 5, Kraft became one of the original 33 personnel (25 of them engineers) to be assigned.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] This marked the beginning of America's man-in-space program, which came to be called Project Mercury.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] As a member of the Space Task Group, Kraft was assigned to the flight operations division, which made plans and arrangements for the operation of the Mercury spacecraft during flight and for the control and monitoring of missions from the ground.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft became the assistant to Chuck Mathews, the head of the division, and was given the responsibility of putting together a mission plan.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] When Kraft began to plan NASA's flight operations, no human being had yet flown in space.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In fact, the task before him was vast, requiring attention to flight plans, timelines, procedures, mission rules, spacecraft tracking, telemetry, ground support, telecommunications networks and contingency management.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] One of Kraft's most important contributions to crewed spaceflight would be his origination of the concept of a mission control center.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Many of the engineers in Project Mercury had previously worked on the flight test of aircraft, where the role for ground support was minimal.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft soon realized that an astronaut could only do so much, particularly during the fast-moving launch phase; the Mercury spacecraft would require real time monitoring and support from specialist engineers.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] These concepts shaped the Mercury Control Center, which was at Cape Canaveral in Florida.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Another important concept pioneered by Kraft was the idea of the flight director, the man who would coordinate the team of engineers and make real-time decisions about the conduct of the mission.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] As Mathews later recalled, Kraft came to him one day saying, "There needs to be someone in charge of the flights while they're actually going on, and I want to be that person." In this informal way, the position of flight director was created.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] A pivotal experience for Kraft was the flight of Mercury-Atlas 5, which sent a chimpanzee named Enos on the first American orbital spaceflight carrying a live passenger.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Coverage of these early missions that carried non-human passengers could often be tongue-in-cheek; a *Time* magazine article on the flight, for example, was titled "Meditative Chimponaut".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Yet Kraft viewed them as important tests for the men and procedures of Mission Control, and as rehearsals for the crewed missions that would follow.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Originally, the flight of Mercury-Atlas 5 had been intended to last for three orbits.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The failure of one of the hydrogen peroxide jets controlling the spacecraft's attitude forced Kraft to make the decision to bring the capsule back to Earth after two orbits.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] It gave him a sense of the responsibility he would have for the lives of others, whether human or chimpanzee.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft served as flight director during all six of the crewed Mercury missions.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] During the final flight—Mercury-Atlas 9, which lasted for over a day—he shared responsibility with his deputy John Hodge.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Mercury-Atlas 6, the February 20, 1962, flight of John Glenn, was a testing experience both for Mission Control and for Kraft.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Space historians Charles Murray and Catherine Bly Cox described it as "the single event that decisively shaped Flight Operations".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The mission was the first orbital flight by an American, and unfolded normally until Glenn began his second orbit.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] At that point Kraft's systems controller, Don Arabian, reported that telemetry was showing a "Segment 51" indicator.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] This suggested that the capsule's landing bag, which was meant to deploy upon splashdown in order to provide a cushion, might have deployed early.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft believed that the Segment 51 indicator was due to faulty instrumentation rather than to an actual early deployment.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] If he was wrong, it would mean that the capsule's heat shield, which fitted on top of the landing bag, was now loose.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] A loose heat shield could cause the capsule to burn up during re-entry.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On consulting with his flight controllers, Kraft became convinced that the indication was false, and that no action was needed.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] His superiors, including Mercury capsule designer Max Faget, overruled Kraft, telling him to instruct Glenn to leave the capsule's retrorocket package on during re-entry.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The reasoning was that the package, which was strapped over the heat shield, would hold the heat shield in place if it was loose.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft, however, felt that this was an unacceptable risk.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] "If any of three retrorockets had solid fuel remaining, an explosion could rip everything apart." Yet he agreed to follow the plan advocated by Faget and by Walt Williams, his superior in the flight operations division.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Glenn landed safely, but an inspection of his capsule revealed that one of the landing bag switches had been faulty.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was right; the heat shield had not been loose after all.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The lessons that he drew from this experience were clear.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Before the flight of Mercury-Atlas 7, Kraft had objected to the choice of Scott Carpenter as the astronaut for the mission, telling Walt Williams that Carpenter's lack of engineering skills might put the mission or his own life in danger.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The mission suffered from problems including an unusually high rate of fuel usage, a malfunctioning horizon indicator, a delayed retrofire for re-entry, and a splashdown that was 250 nmi (460 km) downrange from the target area.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Throughout the mission, Kraft found himself frustrated by the vagueness of Carpenter's communications with Mission Control, and what he perceived as Carpenter's inattention to his duties.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] While some of these problems were due to mechanical failures, and responsibility for some of the others is still being debated, Kraft did not hesitate to assign blame to Carpenter, and continued to speak out about the mission for decades afterwards.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] His autobiography, written in 2001, reopened the issue; the chapter that dealt with the flight of Mercury-Atlas 7 was titled "The Man Malfunctioned".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In a letter to *The New York Times*, Carpenter called the book "vindictive and skewed", and offered a different assessment of the reasons for Kraft's frustration: "in space things happen so fast that only the pilot knows what to do, and even ground control can't help.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] During the Gemini program, Kraft's role changed again.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He was now the head of mission operations, in charge of a team of flight directors, although still also serving as a flight director.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Due to the greater length of Gemini missions, Mission Control was now manned on a three-shift basis.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The Gemini program represented a string of firsts for NASA—the first flight with two astronauts, the first rendezvous in space, the first spacewalk—and Kraft was on duty during many of these historic events.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] America's first spacewalk happened during the Gemini 4 mission; Kraft, at his console, found that he had to force himself to concentrate on his work, distracted by Ed White's "mesmerizing" descriptions of the Earth below.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He could easily understand the euphoria that White felt at the spectacle, yet he also was mindful of the discipline required to keep the flight safe.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] White delayed his return to the capsule, and a communication problem prevented capsule communicator Gus Grissom from getting the crew to hear the order to terminate the spacewalk.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] After Gemini 7, Kraft stepped back from his work at Mission Control, allowing other flight directors to take charge of the remaining missions so that he could devote more time to planning for the Apollo program.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He served on two review boards at North American Aviation, the contractor responsible for the Apollo capsule.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Yet Kraft still felt pangs at not being at the center of the action, particularly after the emergency re-entry of Gemini 8.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Both astronauts and mission controllers had made the right decisions, but, as Kraft confessed to Robert Gilruth, he found himself wishing that he had been the one on the spot.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] With the beginning of the Apollo program, Kraft expected to resume at Mission Control.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He would have been lead flight director on the first crewed Apollo mission (later known as Apollo 1), scheduled to launch in early 1967.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On January 27, 1967, the three crew members were killed in a fire during a countdown test on the pad.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] At the time, Kraft was in Mission Control in Houston, listening in on the Cape test conductor's voice loop.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] There was nothing anyone could do; before the crew at the pad could get the door open, the three astronauts were dead, having been overcome by toxic gases.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was asked by Betty Grissom, the widow of astronaut Gus Grissom, to be one of the pallbearers at Grissom's funeral at Arlington National Cemetery, Virginia.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was a household name in America throughout the 1960s.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He appeared on the cover of the August 27, 1965, issue of *Time*, profiled as the "Conductor in a Command Post".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In the article, he compared himself to Christopher Columbus, and displayed what the magazine described as "an almost angry pride" in his work.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] "We know a lot more about what we have to do than he did" Kraft said.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] "And we know where we're going." The article described Kraft's role in the Gemini 5 mission, and drew on his frequent comparisons of his position as flight director with that of an orchestra conductor.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was surprised at *Time*'s decision to put him on the cover and told the NASA public affairs officer that "they've got the wrong guy.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] It should be Bob Gilruth ... not me." He eventually came to terms with the idea, and the portrait painted for the cover became one of his prized possessions.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] After John Glenn's flight, Kraft had vowed that he would no longer allow his decisions as flight director to be overruled by anyone outside Mission Control.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Occasionally, Kraft intervened in order to ensure that his conception of the flight director's authority was maintained.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] By the time that the Apollo 7 mission flew, he had been promoted to head of the flight operations division; thus, it was Glynn Lunney who served as lead flight director and had to deal directly with behavior by the crew that Kraft considered "insubordinate".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] As Kraft commented in his memoirs, "it was like having a ringside seat at the Wally Schirra Bitch Circus".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Mission commander Wally Schirra, annoyed by last-minute changes in the crew's schedule and suffering from a bad cold, repeatedly refused to accept orders from the ground.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Although Schirra's actions were successful in the short term, Kraft decreed in consultation with astronaut chief Deke Slayton that none of the Apollo 7 crew would fly again.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Schirra had decided before the flight that he would retire after Apollo 7.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft had made a similar pronouncement before, in the case of astronaut Scott Carpenter.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] After the Apollo 1 fire in 1967, Kraft had reluctantly concluded that his responsibilities as a manager would keep him from serving as a flight director on the next crewed mission, Apollo 7, and on missions thereafter.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Henceforth his involvement in the Apollo program would be at a higher level.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] As the director of Flight Operations, Kraft was closely involved in planning the broad outlines of the program.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He was one of the first NASA managers to become involved in the decision to send Apollo 8 on a circumlunar flight.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Due to problems with Lunar Module development in 1968, NASA faced the possibility of a full Apollo test mission being delayed until 1969.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] As a substitute, George Low, the manager of the Apollo Spacecraft Program Office, came up with the idea of assigning a new mission profile to Apollo 8, one that could be flown without the lunar module.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Low's plan was to fly the mission in December, which left little time for the flight operations division to train and prepare.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] After agreeing that the mission was possible in principle, Kraft went to his mission planners and flight directors to determine whether they and their teams could be ready within the projected tight schedule.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] "My head was abuzz with the things we'd have to do," remembered Kraft.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On August 9, Gilruth, Low, Kraft and Slayton flew to Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Alabama, where they briefed NASA managers including Wernher von Braun and Rocco Petrone on the planned mission.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On August 14, they, along with the Huntsville group, traveled to NASA Headquarters in Washington, D.C. to brief Deputy Administrator Thomas O.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In turn, Paine recommended the mission to Administrator James E.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Webb, who gave Kraft and his colleagues the authority to begin preparations for the mission.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In planning for Apollo 8, one of Kraft's responsibilities was ensuring that a fleet would be waiting to recover the crew when they splashed down at the end of the mission.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] This proved an unusual challenge, because much of the Navy's Pacific Fleet would be on leave over the Christmas and New Year's Eve period.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft had to personally meet with Admiral John McCain to persuade him to make the requisite resources available to NASA.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On Christmas Eve, 1968, Apollo 8 went into orbit around the Moon.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Only ten years earlier, Kraft had joined Gilruth's newly founded Space Task Group.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Now, the two men sat together in Mission Control, reflecting on how far they had come.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Around them, the room was filled with cheers, but Kraft and Gilruth celebrated more quietly.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft again found himself a spectator during the landing of Apollo 11, which he viewed from Mission Control, sitting with Gilruth and George Low.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He played a more active role in events during the unfolding of the Apollo 13 crisis.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Called into Mission Control by Gene Kranz almost immediately after the accident, he led discussions on whether Apollo 13 should attempt a direct abort, or go around the Moon and return on a free trajectory; the latter option was taken.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Many Apollo engineers, later to become top managers, considered Kraft to have been one of the best managers in the program.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He personally hand-picked and trained an entire generation of NASA flight directors, including John Hodge, Glynn Lunney and Gene Kranz, the last of whom referred to Kraft as "The Teacher".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The principles that Kraft had inculcated continued to have an impact at Johnson Space Center long after he retired.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft could, however, be a tough taskmaster, making it clear that there was no place in the flight operations division for those who failed to live up to his exacting standards.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] "To err is human", went one of his favorite sayings, "but to do so more than once is contrary to Flight Operations Directorate policy." Subordinates who seriously displeased Kraft could find themselves deprived of the opportunity to make it up to him.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1969, Kraft was named deputy director of the Manned Spacecraft Center (MSC).
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] On January 14, 1972, he became the director of the MSC, replacing Gilruth, for whom Kraft had worked since his arrival at Langley in 1945.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Space commentator Anthony Young has described Kraft as a "superb successor" to Gilruth, second only to him in the history of center directors.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was eligible to retire in the early 1980s, but he chose not to take the option.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He remained as center director in the status of a "reemployed annuitant," receiving his government pension, but still employed by NASA.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1981 he had been involved in a conflict with the NASA Administrator and other top officials over the conduct of the STS-2 mission, and over issues relating to NASA organization and management.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] This contributed to making his position at NASA more tenuous.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In April 1982, Kraft made what newspaper reports called a "surprise announcement" that he intended to step down as center director at the end of the year.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He denied that his resignation had anything to do with the threatened possibility of Johnson Space Center losing its leading role in Space Shuttle operations or in the development of NASA's Space Station Freedom.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] After his retirement, Kraft served as a consultant for Rockwell International and IBM, and as director-at-large of the Houston Chamber of Commerce.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1994, he was appointed chairman of the space shuttle management independent review team, a panel made up of leading aerospace experts, whose remit was to investigate how NASA could make its Space Shuttle program more cost effective.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The panel's report, known as the *Kraft report*, was published in February 1995.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The report was controversial even at the time of its publication.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] John Pike, space policy director for the Federation of American Scientists, commented that "the *Kraft report* is a recipe for disaster.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Nine years later, the *Kraft report* was again criticized, this time by the *Columbia* Accident Investigation Board (CAIB) as part of its consideration of the organizational and cultural causes of the *Columbia* disaster.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 2001, Kraft published his autobiography, *Flight: My Life in Mission Control*.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] It dealt with his life up until the end of the Apollo program, only briefly mentioning his time as center director in the epilogue.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] *The New York Times* review space writer Henry S.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Cooper Jr. called it a "highly readable memoir", while the *Kirkus Review* summed it up as a "[s]nappy, highly detailed account of ...
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] 20th century America's most dramatic technological achievement." Reviewers almost unanimously commented on the outspokenness of Kraft's storytelling, and his readiness to personally criticize those with whom he had disagreed.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Cooper noted that Kraft "pull[s] no punches about some of [his colleagues'] shortcomings", and *Kliatt* magazine said that he "isn't afraid to name names".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1950, Kraft married Betty Anne Kraft (née Turnbull) whom he had met in high school.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] They had two children, Gordon and Kristi-Anne.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was an Episcopalian, serving as a lay reader at his local church.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] During the sixties, the Kraft family was deeply involved in church activities: Betty Anne taught Sunday school and served on the altar guild; Gordon was an acolyte; and Kristi-Anne sang in the choir.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In addition to his duties as a lay reader, Kraft spent some time teaching a class in adult Bible study.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft had been an avid golfer ever since he was introduced to the game in the 1940s by his friend and NASA colleague Sig Sjoberg.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He cited the good golfing as a reason for staying in Houston after his retirement.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft died on July 22, 2019, in Houston, aged 95, two days after the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 moonwalks.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft received numerous awards and honors for his work.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] At the end of the Mercury program, he was invited to attend a ceremony in the White House Rose Garden, where he received the NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal from President John F.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kennedy and Administrator of NASA James E.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] "None of us have many days in our lives like that one," Kraft remembered.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The NASA Distinguished Service Medal was awarded to him twice in 1969 (for Apollo 8 and Apollo 11), in 1981 for the Space Shuttle, and in 1982 as a special award.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He won the Distinguished Citizen Award, given to him by the city of Hampton, Virginia in 1966; the John J.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Montgomery Award in 1963; the ASME Medal in 1973; and the Goddard Memorial Trophy, awarded by the National Space Club, and the Roger W.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Jones Award for Executive Leadership in 1979.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 1999, he was awarded the National Space Trophy from the Rotary National Award for Space Achievement Foundation, which described him as "a driving force in the U.S. human space flight program from its beginnings to the Space Shuttle era, a man whose accomplishments have become legendary".
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 2006, NASA gave Kraft the Ambassador of Exploration Award, which carried with it a sample of lunar material brought back by Apollo 11.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft in turn presented the award to his alma mater, Virginia Tech, for display in its College of Engineering.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He was inducted into the National Aviation Hall of Fame, on October 1, 2016.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] The Mission Control Center at the Johnson Space Center was renamed the *Christopher C.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Mission Control Center* in his honor in 2011, and Kraft Elementary School in Hampton, Virginia, near his hometown, was named for him.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] Kraft was portrayed by Stephen Root in the 1998 miniseries *From the Earth to the Moon*.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] He has been interviewed in numerous documentaries about the space program, including *Apollo 13: To the Edge and Back* (PBS).
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 2018, he was portrayed in the film *First Man* by J.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In 2020, he was portrayed in the mini-series *The Right Stuff* by Eric Ladin.
[src:christopher-c-kraft-jr/christopher-c-kraft-jr] In the 2019 BBC Proms live performance of their album *The Race for Space*, a few days after Kraft's death, Public Service Broadcasting dedicated their performance of "Go!" to Kraft's memory.
